# db-intelligence module layout

`DbIntelligenceModule` exposes HTTP **features** and shared **services** (no controllers on services).

## Top level

| Path | Role |
| --- | --- |
| `features/` | User-facing HTTP: `*.controller.ts`, feature `*.service.ts`, feature-local `*.types.ts`, prompts |
| `services/` | Internal Nest providers consumed by features (and each other only when dependency is clear) |
| `docs/` | Module and per-feature documentation |
| `db-intelligence.module.ts`, `db-intelligence.config.ts` | Module wiring and config |

**Import direction:** `features/` → `services/` only. Services must not import from `features/`.

## Inside `services/<name>/`

| Subfolder / file | Contents |
| --- | --- |
| `<name>.service.ts` | Injectable at service root |
| `types/` | Shared interfaces, enums, type aliases for this service (no runtime logic) |
| `helpers/` | Pure functions + colocated `*.spec.ts` |

**Naming in `helpers/`:** files that export exactly one function → `<kebab-name>.function.ts` with colocated `*.function.spec.ts`. Colocated types/interfaces for that function stay in the same file. Files that also export constants, multiple functions, or shared types keep plain `*.ts` (e.g. `assemble-database-schema.ts`, `schema-for-llm.ts`, `classify-select-risk.ts`).

**Naming in `types/`:** interfaces and type aliases → `*.types.ts` (e.g. `schema.types.ts`, `raw-rows.types.ts`); enums → `*.enum.ts`. Do not add bare `*.ts` type files without the suffix.

Do not add `*.controller.ts` under `services/`.

Example — `services/schema-intelligence/`:

```
schema-intelligence.service.ts
types/          # schema.types.ts, raw-rows.types.ts, field-category.enum.ts
helpers/        # classify-*.function.ts, effective-char-max-length.function.ts, schema-for-llm.ts
```

Schema snapshot types are owned here; features import `types/` or `helpers/` as needed.

## Inside `features/<name>/`

| Location | Contents |
| --- | --- |
| Feature root | `*.controller.ts`, `*.service.ts`, `*.types.ts`, `*.prompt.ts` |
| `helpers/` | Pure functions for this feature only (if needed) |

Feature-specific DTOs/result types stay in the feature root (`text-to-sql.types.ts`), not in `services/`.

## Shared providers

- **LLM:** only `services/llm/llm.service.ts` constructs the OpenAI client.
- **SQL execution:** only `SchemaIntelligenceService.executeReadOnlyQuery` runs SQL (read-only guard).

## What not to add

- Top-level `controllers/`, `utils/`, or duplicate `types/` at module root.
- HTTP routes for internal services (e.g. raw schema export) unless explicitly requested.

## Documentation and file headers

**Docs mirror code layout:** `docs/features/<feature>.md`, `docs/services/<service>.md`, overview in `docs/README.md`. When you add or change domain types, classifiers, or non-obvious behavior, update the matching doc (tables, mappings, examples)—not only code.

**File-level JSDoc header** (see also workspace `comments.mdc`) — always the **first thing in the file, above imports** (never between imports and code):

- `db-intelligence.module.ts` — required. What the Nest module wires (`forRoot` providers, controllers, layering rule). Not a duplicate of `docs/README.md` tables.
- `types/*.types.ts`, `types/*.enum.ts` — required when the file exports snapshot/domain types consumers rely on.
- `helpers/*.function.ts` with non-trivial domain rules — required (e.g. `build-foreign-keys.function.ts`, `assemble-database-schema.ts`). Skip only when a single trivial export needs no extra context (`classify-column.function.ts`).
- `*.service.ts` — required. Describes the file’s orchestration role, not the `@Injectable()` class. Do not add a separate class-level JSDoc unless it documents something the file header does not.

Do not also put a second file-level block above an individual export; one header per file.

Header content (keep compact):

1. What the file owns and key design constraints (why, not a line-by-line map). For services, state the orchestration flow and any non-obvious error semantics (e.g. which failures map to 502 vs 500).
2. Last line: relative path to the canonical doc, e.g. `Behaviour and testing: docs/features/text-to-sql.md`.

Do **not** duplicate long tables or `DATA_TYPE` mappings in the header—that belongs in the doc. The doc should list the same types/exports and link back to source paths (see `docs/services/schema-intelligence.md`).

**Private method JSDoc** — selective, not blanket. Document a private method only when its name + signature do not convey intent, or when it has non-obvious behaviour (error mapping, domain constraints, why-not-X). Leave self-explanatory one-liners and `assert*` guards bare; a redundant doc on an obvious method is noise that `comments.mdc` prohibits. A non-obvious detail local to a few lines is better as an inline comment than a method header.

**Reference pair:** `types/schema.types.ts` + `types/field-category.enum.ts` ↔ `docs/services/schema-intelligence.md`.

More detail: `docs/README.md` (documentation conventions), `docs/features/text-to-sql.md`, and `AGENTS.md.off` (behavior, errors, testing).
